Title: Airborne LiDAR Sampling Strategies to Enhance Forest Aboveground Biomass Estimation from Landsat Imagery
Abstract: Forest aboveground biomass (AGB) estimation over large areas requires the integration of field plots, remotely sensed data, and modeling approaches. Airborne LiDAR provides high-accuracy structural measurements but at high cost, while Landsat imagery offers broad spatial coverage at low cost. We evaluated the effectiveness of systematic, random, and stratified sampling designs for LiDAR acquisitions to calibrate AGB models based on Landsat spectral metrics across a boreal forest landscape. Stratified sampling based on forest age and species composition strata yielded the lowest root mean square error (RMSE) and bias in AGB estimates at the landscape scale. Our results indicate that carefully designed LiDAR sampling can reduce the number of LiDAR strips required by up to 40% while maintaining prediction accuracy, providing a cost-effective pathway for regional AGB mapping programs.

