Title: Tree Diversity and Canopy Structure Drive Understory Plant Diversity in Temperate European Forests
Abstract: Biodiversity-ecosystem functioning relationships in forests are mediated by the vertical structure created by diverse tree assemblages. We analyzed understory plant species richness and composition across 180 forest stands in central Europe spanning a gradient from monocultures to highly diverse mixed stands. Tree species richness and canopy structural complexity, quantified as the coefficient of variation of LiDAR-derived canopy height, jointly explained 52% of the variance in understory plant diversity. The diversity-promoting effect of canopy complexity was most pronounced in stands experiencing moderate levels of light availability, suggesting a hump-shaped relationship between overstory canopy closure and understory richness. These findings have direct implications for close-to-nature silviculture prescriptions aimed at maximizing biodiversity co-benefits in managed forests.

