Abstract: Understanding how landscape features shape gene flow among tree populations is essential for predicting their adaptive capacity under climate change. We sampled European beech (Fagus sylvatica) from 42 populations spanning a 1,200 km latitudinal gradient and genotyped individuals at 12,000 SNP loci via reduced-representation sequencing. Isolation-by-resistance models incorporating forest cover, elevation, and road density explained genetic differentiation substantially better than isolation-by-distance models alone. We identified three genetically distinct regional clusters corresponding to refugial lineages, with limited contemporary gene flow across major agricultural and urban fragmentation barriers. Populations at the warm-rear edge showed the greatest differentiation and lowest genetic diversity, highlighting their vulnerability to future climate warming.

